summary:
Done.
The "needle" was a race condition in the counter service's increment logic. The code used a non-atomic read-modify-write pattern, causing lost updates when multiple increments occurred concurrently. I replaced this with the atomic Redis `INCR` command and updated the corresponding documentation in `app/counter.js`. Verification was successful by running the provided `test.sh` script.

```javascript
// Before fix:
async function incrementCounter() {
  const client = createClient();
  const current = await client.get(COUNTER_KEY);
  const value = parseInt(current || "0", 10);
  const newValue = value + 1;
  await client.set(COUNTER_KEY, newValue.toString());
  return newValue;
}

// After fix:
async function incrementCounter() {
  const client = createClient();
  const newValue = await client.incr(COUNTER_KEY);
  return newValue;
}
```
